text: These words circulate throughout occult and magical circles. They are recorded in Hermetic texts, although they originated in the Vedas.[citation needed]  The actual text of that maxim, as translated by Dennis W. Hauck from The Emerald Tablet of Hermes Trismegistus, is: "That which is Below corresponds to that which is Above, and that which is Above corresponds to that which is Below, to accomplish the miracle of the One Thing."[32] Thus, whatever happens on any level of reality (physical, emotional, or mental) also happens on every other level.  This principle, however, is more often used in the sense of the microcosm and the macrocosm. The microcosm is oneself, and the macrocosm is the universe. The macrocosm is as the microcosm and vice versa; within each lies the other, and through understanding one (usually the microcosm) a man may understand the other.[33]  As Above, So Below is from Hermes Trismegistus.  Movie looks dumb.

text: This movie is such a rip off, it's been done over and over. In hospitals, in mental institutions, I saw this same movie synopsis in a prison, they do this in haunted houses, I lost count of how many times I've watched while some airhead character is in the dark, hears a sound and then says "hey guys did you hear that?" And they build the story up with cheap, not-so-scary scares until their suspicions are finally realized that, YES, there's fucking ghosts or a monster and either 1- everyone dies except the cute couple that never got a chance to finish fucking or 2- only one man or woman escapes alive and they end up going straight jacket crazy, or live the rest of their life with the dark secret of what happened or 3- the mystery of the haunting is shown to the viewer, but it's too late for our 20-something hipster idiots because they all die in horrible gory fashion as the last sorry sucker finds out the truth, then dies. The end.   Until part 2, comes out and they milk the franchise up to part 13 and we all die of fucking boredom. Yep... think I'm gonna skip this.

text: Can people stop being whiny little bitches about every horror film that comes out? For once, just lay off and give it a break. Everyone in the comments section are making petty and snide comments about what MAY be wrong with this film. If you're going to sit there and slag off every horror film that comes out just because it doesn't match up to the likes of The Evil Dead or The Exorcist, then you're going to waste a lot of your own time. Some of the greatest horror films ever made were done on extremely low budgets with poor actors, terrible special effects and huge plot holes. Just because this may not be viewed as a great and iconic horror film in 30 years time, doesn't mean you have to go all keyboard-warrior on it.  Let's also not forget that people have been making horror films for almost 100 years now; if you're still going to demand something completely original and never-seen-before after 100 years of horror films, then you're clearly never going to be satisfied. Besides, this looks like it has a lot of potential and I'll definitely go and see it.

text: For those asking about if any of this is based on real things; the catacombs are real. They are a labrynth of tunnels that are underneath Paris. It is currently illegal to go inside them without authorities permission. Even then it's rare due to how easily you can get lost in there and are officially classed as dangerous due to this. A man is known to have gone missing down there and he was never found again. It is due to this event that authorities stress not to go down there as you can get lost so easily and never find your way out. In regards to hauntings and stuff, it's up to you whether you think it is or not. I don't think it's haunted, but i do find it sad that so many bodies and bones in grave pits are unidentified people without rest.

There /are/ the remains of dead people in the catacombs and people /have/ been known to get lost down there. Most of it is closed off to the public but, as we see in the movie, that didn't stop them.  "Is this movie worth seeing?" - Personally, I thought it was really good. This movie had the best ambiance of any horror film I've ever seen and the 'scares' were genuinely scary. :)

text: The place itself, yes it's real. They're the Paris Catacombs of 6 million dead "Residents". On the contrary, the film is entirely fictional. You can actually take a tour of the Catacombes de Paris, many of the ways are blocked, but you can visit pure history. Located south of the former city gate (the "Barrière d’Enfer" at today's Place Denfert-Rochereau). Although this cemetery covers only a small section of underground tunnels comprising "les carrières de Paris" ("the quarries of Paris"), Parisians today often refer to the entire tunnel network as "the catacombs".

text: People who didn't like the movie probably expected to be entertained with the scariest shit but for others it was truly fascinated and captured the creepiness of the catacombs nicely. It also had a lot of pagan symbolism which I quite enjoyed. The ending made me think and instead of the whole movie being "found footage", I think it was made like that to see the characters point of view to make it feel more real *spoiler alert* I have a theory that the main character is in hell the whole time. Hell is repetition where your past would haunt you and you see apparitions of her dead dad in the very beginning. Before the voyage into the catacombs you meet entities you see later on as the demons lik the boy from the burning car who tels her to go see paps and the demon girl from the singing cult freaks. I think she might've been dead the whole time and believes that her life still continued and she follows her dads legacy to find the philosophers stone aka the only way to bring herself back from the dead. The philosophers stone in this story might be an actual thing in hell and those who are fortunate and smart enough to find it can ressurect themselves back into this world. Knowledge is power is also a theme in this movie. I suggest those who are interested in the other messages to rewatch the movie and let your imagination run. Truly underrated movie

text: Those of you who said this movie is dumb are probably either hipsters or have no desire for imagination and delving into historical scriptures.  The movie was astoundingly historical.  If you could do something called paying attention, you'd have understood that the entire movie was based on a lot historical writings and religious scripture.  I'm an atheist of sorts, I won't delve into details of my religious view points.  But this movie has revealed new details of dozens of historical icons that are prevalent in today's society.  I don't mean to bash you guys at all, but please take my word for it.  Watch the movie again, and engross yourself a bit in researching a few of the details of the film.   I promise you'll be absolutely shocked at how.....   I can't even describe it all, just do it.  Lol. :)
author: Ryan Thompson

text: Went into this film with very low expectations and was pleasantly surprised. While it does play out like standard horror film, it is more mysterious/puzzle solving/investigation type movie. It was constantly entertaining, intriguing, creepy and claustrophobic. I liked the cast, their acting was fine and they were not standard horror assholes, although i did not care for them because they were expendable. Production values are good - they filmed it in a real catacombs after all - you almost feel like you're with them and I also give the movie points for having clever twist in the end. Unfortunately the movie is not scary at all, it is not memorable, people should've been smarter than they were, but  you wouldn't have movie otherwise and it is one time watch. Enjoyable nevertheless 3/5.

text: SPOILER ALERT: This MOVIE Fucking Sucks :) It makes NO sense, from beginning to end. This really pretty, extremely intelligent archaeologist wanted to follow in her fathers footsteps to find out what this Arabic cryptic message scrawled on a bull statue that she found in ANOTHER cave just randomly hanging on the wall meant. So she promised these 3 strangers that there'd be gold down below in a catacomb 4 million feet below earth riddled with bones and her map would show them the way once they were far enough below. Once below, they began hallucinating, and their hallucinations began killing them one by one - BUT WAIT- the pretty archaeologist discovers this weird healing stone that can instantly heal your injuries but not bring you back to life. Once they go farther into the cave, the stone no longer works for some reason and the girl runs alllll the way back past their dormant murderous hallucinations, climbed 50 ft back up the cave and remembers exactly where she took the magic stone to put it back. Oh, and I guess the producers forget that where she got the stone, the cave collapsed but was normal when she went back... The she ran allll the way back down the cave and magically healed an injured friend with her own hands. And they escape.  Fin. Go watch, The Babadook.

text: If you actually want to watch a horror movie with substance, this one's for you. Yeah, at first, I was wondering if I'd even finish the movie, because halfway through, I still didn't see why it was labeled a horror. But don't dwell on the genre, or the critic rating. Finish the movie (I suspect some critics were just looking for immediate gratification, and didn't finish it, or hated it, because it's more of a slow burner), and it's very satisfying, and comes full circle (unlike some that just want to set up for a sequel). It is one of those movies you'll probably have to watch multiple times, to fully appreciate the intelligence, and philosophy involved. But once you get it, you'll remember it. Take it from someone who doesn't even really like horror. This is one of my favorite movies ever.
author: Remy Mafia

text: *DAMN!* it's good to see a Found Footage movie that isn't a bajillionth non-budgeted trip to the woods. text: This movie could of have had great potential to lure more people into watching it, but the acting was mediocre and the story was poorly written as it became too predictable in most of the scenes.  I have given it a thumbs up though because it re-introduces many forbidden and forgotten subjects in today's time.  While some people will see this movie as a movie belonging to a genre of either a horror or adventure movie, or both, I see it as an excellent tool to tell people and show people a little bit of the past.  For example, the movie goes into Iran, where it is known that there are known networks of caves (as well as many other places in the Middle East) where at one point in time served as underground corridors for elites and the privileged religious sects to move around or hide.  The movie also goes back in time to mention and discuss perhaps 15,000 year-old Egyptian history and architecture.  It brought viewers into scenes of the Paris Catacombs in a bizarre and twisted perspective, and interestingly tied it together with modern-day myth and folklore.  But for me personally, what drew me in to the film was the introduction of Alchemy, how alchemy sort of developed in Europe, and the mention of the mythical Philosopher's Stone.  Again, these are subjects that have been forgotten by most societies, but despite some of the subjects not being around today, there is ample evidence left behind for us to study and research.  I would recommend the film so that those people who follow history can see and get another perspective idea of many of the subjects mentioned on the film.

text: This movie was one of the best thriller/suspense/horror movies I’ve ever watched. And I’ve watched A LOT of shitty ones.  This had  -depth -mystery -characters who had stories that I wanna know more about -genuine creepiness  -great acting  -a score that felt perfect for every moment in the film that used it -a setting that was terrifyingly claustrophobic  -an interesting relation to Dante’s inferno -an ending that I did not see coming and have been down countless rabbit holes trying to figure out   I mean I could go on and on and gush about this movie all day long. I’m just wondering if the critics that trashed this movie ever truly saw the same movie I did..  I often rewatch it and it never gets any less creepy. I know when things will pop out or show up but I’m still startled when they do. I think it has more to do with being so in to the story that I subconsciously don’t realize that something is about to happen.   If you haven’t watched this yet,  do yourself a favor and watch this soon. It’s a movie that keeps on giving even after multiple views.
